"Michels A., Mayer F.D., Gallon R., Hoffmann R., Serafini S.T.","Fossil fuel saving through a direct solar energy water heating system",2008,"Clean - Soil, Air, Water","36","9",,"743","747",,,10.1002/clen.200700174,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77952374000&partnerID=40&md5=03cec595c8c801902f17bee2ae9a2006","Federal University of Santa Maria, Santa Maria-RS, Brazil","Michels, A., Federal University of Santa Maria, Santa Maria-RS, Brazil; Mayer, F.D., Federal University of Santa Maria, Santa Maria-RS, Brazil; Gallon, R., Federal University of Santa Maria, Santa Maria-RS, Brazil; Hoffmann, R., Federal University of Santa Maria, Santa Maria-RS, Brazil; Serafini, S.T., Federal University of Santa Maria, Santa Maria-RS, Brazil","The global warming and energy crisis is motivating the search for sustainable power sources. The objective of this work is to analyze the economic return and quantify the reduction in the emission of pollutants, when low-cost solar collectors are used as a partial substitute for a boiler that uses fuel oil as the energy source, in order to heat water for the swimming pools of the Physical Education Center, Federal University of Santa Maria. The collectors are made from PVC and other easily acquired materials. The estimations for energy saving are based on a collecting area of 182 m2. From knowledge of the collectors' efficiency, the mathematical demonstration shows a fuel oil saving of 13,174 kg, representing 24% of the total amount consumed per annum. The investment required for the construction and installation of the collectors is US$ 6,445 and the estimated useful live is five years. The internal rate of return is 30%. The emission of pollutants is reduced by a considerable amount of 41,213 kg CO2 equivalent/year. The use of direct sun energy as an alternative power source represents a significant economic interest as well as contributing to the mitigation of greenhouse gases. © 2008 WILEY-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA, 